social_posts.post_text: Happy New Year! Thank you for following us on a record number of 60 actions in 2022! Much gratitude to our many collaborators for inviting us to visualize their messages of justice and liberation. We’re sharing here some photos from actions in 2022 that we didn’t share before. Enjoy!
Tyre Nichols should be alive today. Justice means change.

366 days since Russia launched a full-scale invasion against Ukraine, killing thousands of civilians and sparking a massive refugee crisis. We joined @fem_antiwar_usa in support of @help.ukraine.center.usa in Union Square to mark the grim anniversary and hope for an end to this senseless and cruel war.

Trans Day of Visibility is today! Trans people are facing the brunt of cruel and hateful legislation, when they should be receiving love and support. Please consider joining a rally in your city today, and donate to organizations, groups, or individuals if you can 🏳️‍⚧️

We went out last night as NYC filled with a thick haze of wildfire smoke to bring a message about climate change to the MoMA garden party fundraiser. Impact from climate change is undeniable and increasing, and climate activists gathered to call for the removal of MoMA’s board chair, who is married to the founder of KKR, one of the largest private equity firms in the world and a major stakeholder in oil and gas projects and pollution.

Dear Friends, 
 
Feminists for Jina-NYC invites you to a global joint action, commemorating a year of feminist revolutionary uprisings in Iran, on the anniversary of the state killing of Jina Mahsa Amini. 

When:  Friday Sept. 15, 7 pm
Where:  Union Square, northeast corner, E 17th Street & Broadway

We will gather with our words, music, and a video projection, then march around the square to echo the revolutionary spirit of feminists in Iran. 

Bring your noisemakers: pots & spoons, drums & other instruments, or your vocal cords! Please share widely.
We appreciate it if you respect our no-state flag policy.

join-Feminist Action – Statement on Sept. 15, 2023: 
Jina is the symbol of the struggle to reclaim life: the attainment of equality, justice and liberation from oppression. Iran's State femicide of Jina (Mahsa) Amini and the killing of hundreds of martyrs and thousands of wounded and imprisoned,  has truly ignited the flame of the Jin Jiyan Azadî revolutionary movement, with women, trans and queer people and other oppressed marginalized groups in its forefront. It crossed borders and has united us together in our fight and resistance.

Now on the eve of the anniversary of the murder of Jina, which is but the continuation of femicide politics and systematic misogyny of the Islamic Republic regime, in solidarity with this revolutionary movement, we, a group of feminist collectives outside Iran, call on all those whose aim and ambition is a world free of sexual, gender, class, national, racial, ethnic and religious oppression to participate in street night marches everywhere, where we will loudly shout: 

Liberation is our right, Jina symbol of our fight
Jin Jiyan Azadî

How much more blood must soak the earth? How many bodies must we bury? How many more will die? Enough. Ceasefire now, to start. More work from there.
List of all the recorded names of children killed in the conflict so far.
Ceasefire, now. This is an atrocity.

There are 5 femicides a day in the United States, and this is likely an underestimate. Each of these victims were human beings with hopes and dreams. Some of them might have been people you liked; some might have been people you would not have gotten along with. Some might have fit the profile of a “good” victim; many would not. But each and every one of these people were victims of a political violence that manifests as hatred of women, a political violence central to the maintenance of white supremacist imperialist capitalist patriarchy, a type of violence that the United States does not call by its name. 

But we do. Each year our group memorializes the year’s victims of FEMICIDE, the names we do know and the names we don’t. We will not stop doing this until there is not one more femicide. 

80% of people honored in this memorial come from womencountusa.org. This database is run by one individual - Dawn Wilcox, a full-time nurse who somehow finds the time to conduct this essential data-gathering and investigative work in the absence of any official database. We express our profound gratitude to Dawn. @womencountusa serves as an essential foundation for our advocacy.

We also extend our deep appreciation for @the.illuminator , whose projection not only paid tribute but also played a vital role in amplifying our collective call for awareness.
